@startuml abstract-factory-structure-concrete
' Abstract Factory, Creational. Concrete structure: real classes bound to roles.
' Example: a UI toolkit producing a matched widget family per platform.
' Source: src/ui/factory/*.ts (cite the real files when you adapt this).
!include ../../pattern-preamble.iuml

interface WidgetFactory <<AbstractFactory>> {
  +createButton() : Button
  +createCheckbox() : Checkbox
}
class MacWidgetFactory <<ConcreteFactory>>
class WinWidgetFactory <<ConcreteFactory>>
interface Button <<AbstractProduct>>
interface Checkbox <<AbstractProduct>>
class MacButton <<ConcreteProduct>>
class MacCheckbox <<ConcreteProduct>>
class WinButton <<ConcreteProduct>>
class WinCheckbox <<ConcreteProduct>>
class AppShell <<Client>>

WidgetFactory <|.. MacWidgetFactory
WidgetFactory <|.. WinWidgetFactory
Button <|.. MacButton
Button <|.. WinButton
Checkbox <|.. MacCheckbox
Checkbox <|.. WinCheckbox
MacWidgetFactory ..> MacButton : creates
MacWidgetFactory ..> MacCheckbox : creates
WinWidgetFactory ..> WinButton : creates
WinWidgetFactory ..> WinCheckbox : creates
AppShell --> WidgetFactory
AppShell --> Button
AppShell --> Checkbox

note as N
  Intent: render a platform-consistent widget family without the shell knowing the platform.
  Consequence: a new platform is one factory and one product set; a new widget type touches every factory.
end note
@enduml
